{"questionId":"33028379","questionHtml":"<p>Show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> is always a root of this equation.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>consider&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>attempts to find&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>(A1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>(since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> is odd), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math> has<br><br></p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math> terms so all terms cancel giving&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>R1<br><br></em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>an even number of terms so all terms cancel giving <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>R1<br><br></em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> is always a root&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>AG</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>considers the product of roots of a polynomial equation of degree&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>product of roots is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup></math> (seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>(for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> odd) there are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> reciprocal pairs of roots&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>product of each reciprocal pair is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> (since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> is odd)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>R1</em></strong></p>\n<p>hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> is always a root&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>AG</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 3</strong></p>\n<p>consider&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>considers&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi></mfrac></mfenced></math> with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; (since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> is odd)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>hence&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>hence&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> is always a root&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[4 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33028379","referenceCode":"24N.3.AHL.TZ0.2h","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that -1 is always a root of this equation.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"h","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.12—Factor and remainder theorems, sum and product of roots","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Simple proof"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}